Overall, \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves F1=0.92 (P=1.00, R=0.85,
95\% CI: [0.81, 1.00])
versus syntactic F1=0.46 (P=1.00, R=0.30), a 2$\times$
improvement in F1.
Critically, \textsc{LiquidPy} produces \textbf{zero false positives}
across all 45 benchmarks, well below the $\sim$30\% false positive
threshold identified by Bessey et al.~\cite{bessey10}
for static analysis adoption.
The three false negatives are all in the production suite (Suite~B)
and involve architectural patterns (ConvTranspose2d, adaptive
pooling, dynamic \texttt{view} reshape) that the current
graph extraction does not fully model.

