\subsection{Confidence Scoring}\label{sec:confidence}

Each verification verdict carries a confidence level
(\textsc{High}, \textsc{Medium}, or \textsc{Low}) based on the
information available:
\textsc{High} when all dimensions are concrete and Z3-proven;
\textsc{Medium} when symbolic dimensions are resolved via
contract discovery;
\textsc{Low} for heuristic-based verdicts with missing models.
The \texttt{filter\_by\_confidence} API allows users to suppress
low-confidence warnings in production use.

\subsection{LLM Baseline Comparison}\label{sec:llm-baseline}

We compare \textsc{LiquidPy} against GPT-4.1-nano (a small
language model) on 10 benchmarks (5 buggy, 5 correct).
The LLM receives the source code and is prompted:
``Does this PyTorch nn.Module have a shape mismatch bug?
Answer YES or NO, then explain.''

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{LLM baseline comparison on 10 benchmarks.
  \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves perfect precision; the LLM achieves
  higher recall but with a false positive.}
\label{tab:llm}
\begin{tabular}{lccccccl}
\toprule
\textbf{Tool} & \textbf{TP} & \textbf{FP} & \textbf{TN} & \textbf{FN}
  & \textbf{P} & \textbf{R} & \textbf{F1} \\
\midrule
\textsc{LiquidPy}   & 4 & 0 & 5 & 1 & 1.00 & 0.80 & 0.89 \\
GPT-4.1-nano         & 5 & 1 & 4 & 0 & 0.83 & 1.00 & 0.91 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The LLM achieves higher recall (1.00 vs.\ 0.80) by catching
a residual-connection bug that requires tracking shapes through
a skip connection pattern.
However, \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves perfect precision (1.00
vs.\ 0.83): the LLM produces a false positive on a correct
autoencoder, hallucinating a dimension mismatch that does not
exist.  This illustrates a fundamental tradeoff: the LLM
has no formal model and cannot \emph{prove} correctness,
while \textsc{LiquidPy}'s Z3-backed verification provides
sound guarantees within its supported scope.
Average verification time is 156ms for \textsc{LiquidPy}
versus 4{,}600ms for the LLM API call.

\subsection{Summary of Results}\label{sec:summary}

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Summary of \textsc{LiquidPy} evaluation across 45 benchmarks.}
\label{tab:summary}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lccccl@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Benchmark} & $n$ & \textbf{F1} & \textbf{P} & \textbf{R} &
  \textbf{Key finding} \\
\midrule
Suite A (theory)          & 18 & 1.00 & 1.00 & 1.00 & Z3 theories essential \\
Suite B (production)      & 12 & 0.67 & 1.00 & 0.50 & 3 arch.\ gaps \\
Suite C (symbolic)        &  7 & 1.00 & 1.00 & 1.00 & CEGAR eliminates FPs \\
Discovery ablation        &  8 & 1.00 & 1.00 & 1.00 & no degradation \\
\midrule
\textbf{Overall}          & 45 & 0.92 & 1.00 & 0.85 & 0 false positives \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The most important finding is the \textbf{zero false positive rate}
across all 45 benchmarks.
The three false negatives in Suite~B are due to specific
architectural patterns (ConvTranspose2d, adaptive pooling,
dynamic view) not yet supported by the graph extractor, not
fundamental limitations of the constraint-based approach.
For modules within \textsc{LiquidPy}'s supported layer set
(Linear, Conv2d, BatchNorm, LayerNorm, Dropout, LSTM,
MultiheadAttention, and standard arithmetic/broadcasting),
verification achieves F1=1.00.


%% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{Tensor shape analysis.}
PyTea~\cite{pytea} (ECOOP 2022) is the closest related work,
performing abstract interpretation over PyTorch tensor operations.
PyTea reasons about individual operations and simple sequential
compositions, but does not verify entire \texttt{nn.Module}
computation graphs, track devices, or handle phase-dependent
behavior.
jaxtyping~\cite{jaxtyping}, beartype~\cite{beartype}, and
torchtyping~\cite{torchtyping} provide runtime shape assertions
but no static guarantees.

\paragraph{Abstract interpretation and static analysis.}
\textsc{LiquidPy}'s approach---forward symbolic propagation of
constraints through a data-flow graph---is most closely related to
abstract interpretation~\cite{cousot77} with domain-specific
abstract domains.  The product theory can be viewed as a reduced
product of three abstract domains, with Z3 providing the
concretization.  The key difference is that our abstract domains are
implemented as SMT theories with eager propagation.
Bessey et al.~\cite{bessey10} characterize practical
requirements for static analysis adoption, noting that false
positive rates above $\sim$30\% lead to tool abandonment.

\paragraph{Liquid types and refinement types.}
Liquid types~\cite{rondon08} introduced SMT-checkable
refinement predicates attached to types.
Liquid Haskell~\cite{vazou14} brought this to practice.
\textsc{LiquidPy} contributes the computation graph
verification layer absent from prior refinement type systems.

\paragraph{Counterexample-guided refinement.}
CEGAR~\cite{clarke00} (CAV 2000) is a standard technique in model
checking.  Houdini~\cite{flanagan01} (FME 2001) discovers
annotation candidates by eliminating non-inductive predicates.
\textsc{LiquidPy}'s contract discovery loop is a Houdini-style
predicate accumulation loop, substantially simpler than general
CEGAR: deterministic refinement via layer parameters and
unsat core-based predicate extraction.

\paragraph{Domain-specific SMT theories.}
Custom theory plugins via Z3's \texttt{UserPropagator}
API~\cite{z3userprop} enable domain-specific decision procedures
in the DPLL(T) loop.  \textsc{LiquidPy} contributes the first
theories for tensor operations.

\paragraph{Behavioral neural network verification.}
Reluplex, ERAN, and $\alpha$-$\beta$-CROWN verify
\emph{behavioral} properties (robustness, reachability).
\textsc{LiquidPy} performs \emph{computation graph verification}:
structural correctness of shape compatibility, device consistency,
and phase correctness.
These are complementary.

\paragraph{ML-specific analysis.}
CrossHair~\cite{crosshair} performs symbolic execution of Python
but does not target tensor shapes.
TensorFuzz~\cite{tensorfuzz} applies fuzz testing.
DeepLocalize~\cite{deeplocalize} localizes faults dynamically.


%% ============================================================
\section{Discussion and Limitations}\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Honest positioning.}
\textsc{LiquidPy} is best understood as a constraint-based static
verifier with domain-specific SMT theories for tensor operations,
closer to abstract interpretation with Z3-backed abstract domains
than to classical model checking or behavioral neural network
verification.
The computation graphs we analyze are acyclic DAGs, not Kripke
structures; our contract discovery is Houdini-style predicate
accumulation with Z3-backed abstract feasibility checking (not
concrete Python execution); and we verify structural properties,
not behavioral ones.
The verifier performs constraint-based forward symbolic propagation
on acyclic DAGs using unsat core-based predicate extraction.

\paragraph{False negative analysis.}
The three false negatives in Suite~B stem from the AST-based
graph extractor's inability to track shapes through:
(1)~\texttt{ConvTranspose2d} output channel computation;
(2)~adaptive pooling followed by \texttt{view}-based flattening;
(3)~dynamic \texttt{view} reshape with computed dimensions
(\texttt{x.view(x.size(0), -1)}).
These are engineering limitations, not fundamental to the approach.
Extending the graph extractor to handle these patterns would
eliminate all three false negatives.

\paragraph{False positive analysis.}
\textsc{LiquidPy} produces zero false positives across all
45 benchmarks.  Contract discovery via the CEGAR-inspired loop
eliminates spurious counterexamples from symbolic dimensions:
without contract discovery, 6 of 7 symbolic benchmarks would be
false positives; with contract discovery, all are correctly
classified.

\paragraph{Comparison with PyTea.}
PyTea~\cite{pytea} performs abstract interpretation over individual
tensor operations and simple sequential compositions.
\textsc{LiquidPy} differs in three ways:
(1)~it verifies \emph{composition} of layers across the full
computation graph, not just individual operations;
(2)~it uses Z3 \texttt{UserPropagator} plugins for domain-specific
theory reasoning (broadcasting, stride, device, phase);
(3)~it discovers implicit shape contracts via counterexample-guided
refinement.
A head-to-head comparison on identical benchmarks is planned
for future work.

\paragraph{Other limitations.}
The current AST-based extraction cannot always resolve variable
constructor parameters beyond simple defaults.
Skip connections with channel changes can produce conservative
results when concatenation tracking is incomplete.
Recurrent architectures are not handled by the acyclic assumption.

\paragraph{Future work.}
Extending graph extraction to support ConvTranspose2d,
adaptive pooling, and dynamic \texttt{view} operations.
Adding dtype theory and gradient flow theory.
Scaling to 100+ layer models via incremental verification.
Integration with \texttt{torch.compile}'s symbolic shape
infrastructure (TorchDynamo shape guards, \texttt{torch.export}
Dim constraints).


